<p>On a glass door in the mathematics department at the University of Erlangen–Nürnberg in Germany, this determinant is printed:</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" src="https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/2025-09-16-both-sides-now-1.png" alt="erlangen–nürnberg determinant 1" width="375" height="237" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-71717" srcset="https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/2025-09-16-both-sides-now-1.png 375w, https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/2025-09-16-both-sides-now-1-300x190.png 300w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 375px) 100vw, 375px" /></p>
<p>Sure enough, X · I &#8211; IV · II = II.</p>
<p>Pass through the door and regard it from the other side and you see a different equation:</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" src="https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/2025-09-16-both-sides-now-2.png" alt="erlangen–nürnberg determinant 2" width="375" height="237" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-71718" srcset="https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/2025-09-16-both-sides-now-2.png 375w, https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/2025-09-16-both-sides-now-2-300x190.png 300w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 375px) 100vw, 375px" /></p>
<p>But this too is true: II = VI · II &#8211; X · I.</p>
<p>(Burkard Polster, <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20230705071120/https://www.qedcat.com/articles/ambigram.pdf">&#8220;Mathemagical Ambigrams,&#8221;</a> <em><em>Proceedings of the Mathematics and Art Conference</em></em>, 2000.)</p>
